{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":467,"record_hash":"sha256:d29ec5c1ef53cf35b247957b64cc000b3b7991beeb6be2140a5dbdabd3be1e9e","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:43:43.798Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: ca8852\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1851\nOutput:\n# Agent Trail\n\nAgent Trail is the review-adjacent product surface for captured agent sessions.\nIt is the page a reviewer opens from a pull request to understand the agent work\nbehind a change.\n\n## Working Name\n\nUse **Agent Trail** for now.\n\nGood PR link text:\n\n- View Agent Trail\n- Explore Agent Trail\n- Agent Trail for this PR\n\nAvoid names like \"transcript\", \"audit log\", or \"provenance report\" for the\nproduct surface. The page may contain transcript records and provenance facts,\nbut the user-facing promise is simpler: follow the useful trail behind this\nchange.\n\n## Product Shape\n\nA developer opens a pull request from GitButler or GitHub. GitButler adds a link\nto the pull request. A reviewer clicks that link and lands on a GitButler-owned\nweb page for the Agent Trail.\n\nThe page lets the reviewer explore captured agent context related to the pull\nrequest:\n\n- prompts and requests from the human\n- assistant responses and claims\n- tool calls and tool results\n- tests and validation attempts\n- decisions and tradeoffs\n- follow-up questions\n- edge cases discussed or missed\n\nThis is not primarily a chat transcript viewer. The transcript is the source of\ntruth, but the review experience should be organized around helping a reviewer\nunderstand the change.\n\n## Core Question\n\nAgent Trail should answer:\n\n> What agent context helps me review this pull request?\n\nIt should not claim:\n\n> This agent session authored this pull request.\n\nThe language should stay evidence-based. Say that a session or turn is related\nto a pull request, branch, review, or change. Do not present related agent data\nas proof of authorship.\n\n## Current Decisions\n\n- MVP entry point: on-demand URL replacement.\n- Shareable page shape: generated snapshot, not a live view.\n- Initial access scope: public repositories and public metadata only.\n- Likely host: Forge, outside the GitButler repository.\n- Data interpretation: server-side code links and uses `bu\n[TRUNCATED]\n access, and explicit share\nlinks can come later.\n\nThis entry point should still respect the publication boundary. Rewriting a URL\nshould not automatically expose private captured context. It should create a\nrequest for an Agent Trail, then show one of:\n\n- an existing published trail\n- a newly generated review-safe overview, if access and policy allow it\n- an authentication prompt\n- a clear \"no trail available\" state\n\nOn-demand generation is attractive because it avoids needing every PR to be\npre-linked by GitButler. It also gives reviewers a memorable gesture: replace\nthe forge domain with the Agent Trail domain.\n\nOpen design questions:\n\n- Should generated trails be cached automatically?\n- Who can publish or persist the generated result?\n- What should happen when no captured agentlog data exists for the PR?\n- How should GitHub authentication map to GitMeta/Forge access?\n\n## Data Source\n\nAgent Trail should build on `but-agentlog` primitives:\n\n- durable project-scoped agent sessions\n- capture turns inside sessions\n- transcript records inside turns\n- observed branch, review, and change targets\n- verified related-session lookup\n- bounded turn and record hydration\n\n`but-agentlog` should remain the evidence layer. Agent Trail should live above\nit as a product-specific projection and browsing layer.\n\n## Repository And Hosting Boundary\n\nThe Agent Trail website or service should not live inside the GitButler\nrepository by default.\n\nGitButler should own the local evidence plumbing:\n\n- capture\n- redaction\n- GitMeta storage and sync\n- related-session and related-turn lookup\n- bounded transcript hydration\n- optional PR-link creation metadata\n\nThe hosted Agent Trail product should live outside this repository. The likely\nhome is `/Users/kiril/src/forge`, if the current product direction holds.\n\nForge should own the review product concerns:\n\n- hosted routes and stable URLs\n- authentication and permissions\n- publication flow\n- PR link landing page\n- review-specific ranking and highlighting\n- generated summaries, if added\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:43:43.798Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}